## The one mechanical strip (applied throughout)

The framework computes through the **shape operator** `Ŝ = −(1/|g|) P H_F P` — the
Hessian, metric-normalised (`1/|g|`) and tangent-projected (`P`). That normalisation +
projection **is** the metric. The metric-free replacement:

| Framework (metric) | Cella (connection / coupling, exact ℚ) |
|---|---|
| shape operator `Ŝ` | the exact **second-difference tensor** of the residue account across representation axes (difference tower) |
| principal curvatures (eigenvalues of `Ŝ`) | the difference-tensor's **elementary symmetric functions** (char-poly coefficients) |
| metric normalisation `1/|g|`, projector `P` | **balance / closure** (the books reconcile) |
| extrinsic curvature `K_G` | **intrinsic loop-holonomy** of the residue connection |
| "curvature of the surface" | "obstruction to transporting the account around a loop" |

What survives the strip: the framework's **invariant** content (decompositions, symmetries,
invariances) — because those are connection content. What does *not*: the coordinate-dependent
metric parts (the individual `κ` magnitudes, the `|g|` normalisation). The PROVEN framework
results are mostly the former, which is why so much promotes.

